@NODE INSU "LoTo99 - The Lottery Predictor And Checker Program (Instructions)"
@TOC MAIN
             _  __________________________
             ®| ®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®| @{" Introduction " LINK INTR}
             ®| ____  ®| ____   ____  ____  @{" Warranty     " LINK LAWS}
             ®| ®®®®| ®| ®®®®|  ®®®®| ®®®®| @{" Winware      " LINK WINW}
             ®| ®|_®| ®| ®|_®|  ®|_®| ®|_®| @{" Requirements " LINK REQU}
             ®| ®®®®| ®| ®®®®|  ®®®®| ®®®®| @{" Installation " LINK INST}
             ®|______________   ___®| ___®|  Instructions
             ®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®®|  ®®®®| ®®®®| @{" Future       " LINK FUTU}
 
    LOTO99 was designed to be as easy to use as it could be
    within the GUI. To start the program you need to double
    click on the icon or type its name into the CLI.

    Once you have done this you will be presented with a menu.
    
    The program is split into four main parts, these include:

    · The number generator - this section is used to generate
      random numbers using various methods. (currently only 3)
      once six numbers have been generated you can optionally
      add them to a board on the next section or print them;

    · The database of boards - this is where you enter the
      numbers which need to be checked on the next draw
      (currently twenty five boards for each lottery type). If
      you don't want to use a board then press clear accept;

    · The draw entry section - from here you enter the numbers
      that have just been drawn. They are then used to compare
      with the boards in the previous section and the result is
      sent to the next section, you can now click on the top
      numbers to delete them;

    · The results section - this section shows how many numbers
      match that of which have been drawn.

    · Lottery Type Selector - this is where you choose the type
      of lottery, each lottery type has its own draw database.

@ENDNODE
